<b>
  <d4p_eqn_inline>
    <d4p_MathML><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>A</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⟶</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo>·</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>B</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⟶</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⟶</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⟶</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo>·</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>A</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⟶</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>B</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⟶</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>A</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⟶</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>B</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⟶</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo>·</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⟶</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow></m:math></d4p_MathML>
  </d4p_eqn_inline>.</b>
In words,
<b>we can switch the dot and cross product without changing anything 
  in this entity.</b>
(In either formula of course you must take the cross product first.) This product, like the determinant, changes sign if you just reverse the vectors in the cross product.
<br/>
</p><p>
